This is the guideline I worked with for Deer to my Heart.
"Tribal" anthros (typically wild species), whether they live in the wilds, on a reservation, or in modern society generally consider consuming the flesh of their wild counterpart to be a great taboo, equivalent to cannibalism. They are often seen as spirit guides or reincarnations of family members. This cultural view serves as a point of contention between my romantic leads.
"Settled" anthros (domesticated species, humans are grouped in for shared culture) don't assign much reverence to their non-sapient counterparts, and in rural areas you can often find goat or cattle anthros raising herds of regular goats or cattle. A cow anthro can probably cook you the best steak you've had in your life.
Diet is tangentially relevant so I'll dump my notes on that here too. "Herbivorous" anthros consume animal products and meat, but in lower amounts than humans do, and they are more likely than humans to practice vegetarianism. This is the opposite for anthros that resemble carnivorous species.
